                    <p class="text-lg text-text mb-8">
                        These exercises have been selected based on their proven effectiveness, safety profile, and ease of implementation. Perform these exercises 3-4 times per week, starting gently and gradually increasing duration and repetitions as your strength improves.
                    </p>

                    <!-- Exercise 1: Cat-Cow Stretch -->
                    <div class="card mb-10">
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-primary mb-4">1. Cat-Cow Stretch (Marjaryasana-Bitilasana)</h3>
                        
                        <div class="border-2 border-black rounded-lg px-5 py-6 mb-4">
                            <p class="text-sm text-text mb-2 pl-6 mt-4"><strong>Target Areas:</strong> Entire spine, core muscles, shoulders</p>
                            <p class="text-sm text-text pl-6 mb-4"><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Beginner</p>
                        </div>

                        <p class="text-lg text-text mb-4">
                            This dynamic stretching exercise is excellent for warming up the spine, improving flexibility, and releasing tension throughout the back. The cat-cow stretch mobilizes all regions of the spine while gently engaging your core muscles.
                        </p>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">How to Perform:</h4>
                        <ol class="space-y-3 text-text mb-4 list-decimal list-inside">
                            <li>Start on your hands and knees in a tabletop position, with your wrists directly under your shoulders and knees under your hips.</li>
                            <li>Ensure your spine is in a neutral position, with your back flat and your head in line with your spine.</li>
                            <li><strong>Cow Pose:</strong> As you inhale, drop your belly toward the floor, lift your chest and chin forward and up, and allow your shoulder blades to slide down your back.</li>
                            <li><strong>Cat Pose:</strong> As you exhale, draw your belly toward your spine, arch your back toward the ceiling, and tuck your chin toward your chest.</li>
                            <li>Flow smoothly between these two positions, coordinating movement with your breath.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Recommended Duration:</h4>
                        <p class="text-text mb-4">
                            Perform 10-15 repetitions, moving slowly and smoothly. The entire sequence should take about 2-3 minutes.
                        </p>

                        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-300 px-5 py-6 rounded-lg">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-4 pl-6 mt-4">Pro Tips:</h5>
                            <ul class="space-y-3 text-blue-900 pl-6 mb-4">
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Move slowly and deliberately—this isn't a race</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Keep your breathing smooth and coordinated with movement</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Avoid forcing the movement; let it happen naturally</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>If you have knee pain, place a folded towel under your knees for cushioning</span>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Exercise 2: Bird Dog -->
                    <div class="card mb-10">
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-primary mb-4">2. Bird Dog Exercise</h3>
                        
                        <div class="border-2 border-black rounded-lg px-5 py-6 mb-4">
                            <p class="text-sm text-text mb-2 pl-6 mt-4"><strong>Target Areas:</strong> Core muscles, lower back, glutes, shoulders</p>
                            <p class="text-sm text-text pl-6 mb-4"><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Beginner to Intermediate</p>
                        </div>

                        <p class="text-lg text-text mb-4">
                            The bird dog is a foundational core stability exercise that strengthens the muscles supporting your spine while improving balance and coordination. This exercise teaches your body to maintain a neutral spine position while moving your limbs—a crucial skill for preventing back injuries during daily activities.
                        </p>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">How to Perform:</h4>
                        <ol class="space-y-3 text-text mb-4 list-decimal list-inside">
                            <li>Begin in the tabletop position with your hands under shoulders and knees under hips.</li>
                            <li>Engage your core by gently drawing your belly button toward your spine, maintaining a neutral spine position.</li>
                            <li>Slowly extend your right arm forward and your left leg backward, keeping both parallel to the floor.</li>
                            <li>Hold this position for 5-10 seconds while maintaining a steady breath and stable torso.</li>
                            <li>Return to the starting position with control.</li>
                            <li>Repeat with the opposite arm and leg (left arm, right leg).</li>
                        </ol>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Recommended Sets and Reps:</h4>
                        <p class="text-text mb-4">
                            Perform 3 sets of 10 repetitions on each side (20 total reps per set). Rest 30 seconds between sets.
                        </p>

                        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-300 px-5 py-6 rounded-lg">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-4 pl-6 mt-4">Pro Tips:</h5>
                            <ul class="space-y-3 text-blue-900 pl-6 mb-4">
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Focus on keeping your hips level and square to the floor—avoid rotating</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Don't arch your lower back; maintain a neutral spine throughout</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Start with just arm movements or leg movements if the full exercise is too challenging</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Imagine balancing a glass of water on your lower back to help maintain stability</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Keep your extended arm and leg in line with your torso, not reaching higher</span>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Exercise 3: Pelvic Tilts -->
                    <div class="card mb-10">
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-primary mb-4">3. Pelvic Tilts</h3>
                        
                        <div class="border-2 border-black rounded-lg px-5 py-6 mb-4">
                            <p class="text-sm text-text mb-2 pl-6 mt-4"><strong>Target Areas:</strong> Lower back, abdominal muscles, pelvic floor</p>
                            <p class="text-sm text-text pl-6 mb-4"><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Beginner</p>
                        </div>

                        <p class="text-lg text-text mb-4">
                            Pelvic tilts are a gentle yet effective exercise for mobilizing the lower back and strengthening the deep core muscles. This exercise is particularly beneficial for people experiencing stiffness in the lumbar spine and is safe enough to perform even during acute pain episodes (with your doctor's approval).
                        </p>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">How to Perform:</h4>
                        <ol class="space-y-3 text-text mb-4 list-decimal list-inside">
                            <li>Lie on your back on a comfortable surface (exercise mat or carpet) with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor, hip-width apart.</li>
                            <li>Place your arms by your sides, palms facing down.</li>
                            <li>Relax your lower back into a neutral position—there should be a small natural curve.</li>
                            <li><strong>Posterior Tilt:</strong> As you exhale, gently tilt your pelvis so your lower back presses flat against the floor. You should feel your lower abdominals engage.</li>
                            <li>Hold for 5 seconds while breathing normally.</li>
                            <li><strong>Anterior Tilt:</strong> As you inhale, tilt your pelvis in the opposite direction, slightly arching your lower back and lifting it away from the floor.</li>
                            <li>Rock smoothly between these two positions.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Recommended Duration:</h4>
                        <p class="text-text mb-4">
                            Perform 15-20 repetitions, moving slowly between positions. The exercise should take about 3-4 minutes.
                        </p>

                        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-300 px-5 py-6 rounded-lg">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-4 pl-6 mt-4">Pro Tips:</h5>
                            <ul class="space-y-3 text-blue-900 pl-6 mb-4">
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Keep the movement small and controlled—you're not doing sit-ups</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Focus on using your abdominal muscles, not pushing with your legs</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Keep your upper body and shoulders relaxed throughout</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>This is an excellent exercise to perform first thing in the morning to loosen a stiff back</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Can be performed on your bed if getting down to the floor is difficult</span>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Exercise 4: Knee to Chest Stretch -->
                    <div class="card mb-10">
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-primary mb-4">4. Knee to Chest Stretch</h3>
                        
                        <div class="border-2 border-black rounded-lg px-5 py-6 mb-4">
                            <p class="text-sm text-text mb-2 pl-6 mt-4"><strong>Target Areas:</strong> Lower back, glutes, hip flexors</p>
                            <p class="text-sm text-text pl-6 mb-4"><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Beginner</p>
                        </div>

                        <p class="text-lg text-text mb-4">
                            The knee to chest stretch is a classic therapeutic exercise that gently stretches the lower back muscles and glutes while providing a mild traction effect on the lumbar spine. This exercise is particularly effective for reducing muscle tension and can provide immediate relief for many people experiencing lower back discomfort.
                        </p>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">How to Perform:</h4>
                        <ol class="space-y-3 text-text mb-4 list-decimal list-inside">
                            <li>Lie on your back on a comfortable surface with both legs extended.</li>
                            <li>Bend your right knee and bring it toward your chest, clasping your hands behind your thigh or on top of your shin (whichever is more comfortable).</li>
                            <li>Gently pull your knee closer to your chest until you feel a comfortable stretch in your lower back and buttock. Keep your left leg extended on the floor.</li>
                            <li>Hold this position for 20-30 seconds while breathing deeply and relaxing into the stretch.</li>
                            <li>Slowly release and return to the starting position.</li>
                            <li>Repeat with your left leg.</li>
                            <li>For a deeper stretch, bring both knees to your chest simultaneously.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Recommended Sets and Reps:</h4>
                        <p class="text-text mb-4">
                            Perform 2-3 repetitions on each leg, holding each stretch for 20-30 seconds. Include 2-3 double knee to chest stretches.
                        </p>

                        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-300 px-5 py-6 rounded-lg">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-4 pl-6 mt-4">Pro Tips:</h5>
                            <ul class="space-y-3 text-blue-900 pl-6 mb-4">
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Never force or bounce the stretch—use gentle, steady pressure</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Keep your head and shoulders relaxed on the floor</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>If you feel any sharp pain, reduce the intensity or skip this exercise</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>For the extended leg, actively press it into the floor to increase the stretch</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>This stretch can be performed in bed before getting up in the morning</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Place a small pillow under your head if you find it more comfortable</span>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Exercise 5: Bridge Exercise -->
                    <div class="card mb-10">
                        <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-primary mb-4">5. Bridge Exercise (Glute Bridge)</h3>
                        
                        <div class="border-2 border-black rounded-lg px-5 py-6 mb-4">
                            <p class="text-sm text-text mb-2 pl-6 mt-4"><strong>Target Areas:</strong> Glutes, hamstrings, lower back, core</p>
                            <p class="text-sm text-text pl-6 mb-4"><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Beginner to Intermediate</p>
                        </div>

                        <p class="text-lg text-text mb-4">
                            The bridge exercise is one of the most effective movements for strengthening the posterior chain—the muscles along the back of your body. Strong glutes are essential for back health because they support proper pelvic alignment and reduce stress on the lumbar spine during daily activities like walking, standing, and lifting.
                        </p>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">How to Perform:</h4>
                        <ol class="space-y-3 text-text mb-4 list-decimal list-inside">
                            <li>Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor, positioned hip-width apart. Your feet should be close enough to your hips that you can almost touch your heels with your fingertips.</li>
                            <li>Place your arms by your sides with palms facing down.</li>
                            <li>Engage your core and glutes, then press through your heels to lift your hips toward the ceiling.</li>
                            <li>Continue lifting until your body forms a straight line from shoulders to knees. Your shins should be approximately vertical.</li>
                            <li>Squeeze your glutes at the top of the movement and hold for 2-5 seconds.</li>
                            <li>Slowly lower your hips back to the starting position with control.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Recommended Sets and Reps:</h4>
                        <p class="text-text mb-4">
                            Perform 3 sets of 12-15 repetitions. Rest 30-60 seconds between sets.
                        </p>

                        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-300 px-5 py-6 rounded-lg">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-4 pl-6 mt-4">Pro Tips:</h5>
                            <ul class="space-y-3 text-blue-900 pl-6 mb-4">
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Focus on lifting with your glutes and hamstrings, not by arching your lower back</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Keep your knees in line with your feet—don't let them collapse inward</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Avoid overextending at the top; your body should form a straight line, not an arch</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Press your arms and shoulders firmly into the floor for stability</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>To increase difficulty, try holding the top position for 10-30 seconds, or perform single-leg bridges</span>
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start">
                                    <span class="text-blue-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                                    <span>Breathe out as you lift, breathe in as you lower</span>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

