                <!-- When to Seek Professional Help -->
                <section class="mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-heading font-bold text-text mb-6">When to Seek Professional Help</h2>
                    
                    <p class="text-lg text-text mb-6">
                        While these exercises are safe and effective for most people with non-specific lower back pain, certain symptoms warrant immediate professional evaluation:
                    </p>

                    <div class="card bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 mb-6">
                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Seek Immediate Medical Attention If You Experience:</h4>
                        <ul class="space-y-2 text-text">
                            <li>• Loss of bladder or bowel control</li>
                            <li>• Progressive weakness in your legs</li>
                            <li>• Numbness in the groin or inner thigh area (saddle anesthesia)</li>
                            <li>• Severe pain that doesn't improve with rest</li>
                            <li>• Pain accompanied by fever, chills, or unexplained weight loss</li>
                            <li>• Back pain following significant trauma (such as a fall or accident)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="card mb-6">
                        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-3">Consider Consulting a Healthcare Professional If:</h4>
                        <ul class="space-y-2 text-text">
                            <li>• Your pain persists for more than 6 weeks despite home treatment</li>
                            <li>• Pain significantly interferes with your daily activities or work</li>
                            <li>• You experience numbness or tingling that spreads down your legs</li>
                            <li>• Your pain is worse at night or when lying down</li>
                            <li>• You have a history of cancer, osteoporosis, or steroid use</li>
                            <li>• You're over 50 and experiencing your first episode of significant back pain</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="text-lg text-text mb-6">
                        Allied health professionals such as physiotherapists, chiropractors, and osteopaths can provide personalised assessment and treatment plans tailored to your specific condition. They can also modify these exercises based on your individual needs and limitations.
                    </p>
                </section>

